Icon.name: Icon
Icon.description:
Icon component that enables stable color and interaction overrides.

To change the icon, swap the component the level below the Color Union layer and select another icon from the Astro UXDS Icons library.

Status Symbol.name: Status Symbol
Status Symbol.description: The Status Symbol combines color and shape to create a standard and consistent way to indicate the status of a device or feature.

Accordion Group.name: Accordion Group
Accordion Group.description:
An Accordion Group is a component which presents a hierarchical set of items in which different branches of that hierarchy may be exposed at any time.

Slot:
The expanded accordion items have a slot, which is hidden by default, that users can activate and swap out for customized local components or other pre-built components.

Accordion Item.name: Accordion Item
Accordion Item.description:
An Accordion Item is a single instance that allows a user to structure their own Accordion Group or to use if only a single instance is needed. There is a left icon that is hidden by default.

Slot:
The expanded accordion items have a slot, which is hidden by default, that users can activate and swap out for customized local components or other pre-built components.

Primary Button.name: Primary Button
Primary Button.description:
Primary Buttons allow users to trigger actions by clicking, tapping, or pressing a corresponding key on a keyboard, such as the Enter key.

We recommend that you use the default button heights.

Secondary Button.name: Secondary Button
Secondary Button.description:
Secondary Buttons are an alternative button style to be used in situations where a de-emphasized button is beneficial in guiding the user to a preferred option.

We recommend that you use the default button heights.

Borderless Button.name: Borderless Button
Borderless Button.description:
Borderless Buttons are a tertiary, alternative button style to be used in situations where a further de-emphasized button is beneficial in guiding the user to a preferred option.

The different sizes change the heights of the component. We recommend that you use the default button heights.

Card.name: Card
Card.description:
A card used for small groupings of content that sits on top of a container.

To use your own custom content to in the body of the card, replace the Slot instance with an instance of your own custom content component.

Any padding desired in the body section should be built into the content component that you override the slot with. The base component body does not include built-in padding.

NOTE: There is currently no coded version or documentation at this time.

Checkbox Group.name: Checkbox Group
Checkbox Group.description:
Use a Checkbox group when there is a group or a nested set of a list of options from which the user may select any number of choices.

Users should turn component selection options including indented checkboxes and text on and off in the layer menu as needed. Group borders can be toggled off and on using the properties tab on the right hand panel.

Checkbox.name: Checkbox
Checkbox.description:
Use Checkboxes when there is a list of options from which the user may select any number of choices.

Users should turn component selection options and text on and off in the layer menu as needed.

Portion Marking.name: Portion Marking
Portion Marking.description: Classification and control markings are required for digital products created for government clients who interact with classified or controlled information. This is an optional visual design for portion markings.

Classification Banner.name: Classification Banner
Classification Banner.description: Classification and control markings are required for digital products created for government clients who interact with classified or controlled information.

Clock.name: Clock
Clock.description:
Clock shows the current date (optional) and time, and optional AOS and LOS timers. It will typically be positioned on the Global Status Bar.

Portions of the clock can be turned on and off using the layers menu show/hide icon, and the bottom label containers can be manipulated using the right hand properties panel.

Parent Container.name: Parent Container
Parent Container.description:
A container used for large groupings of content that sits on top of the background surface of the app or is used as a panel or dialog above the existing UI.

If the container is being used in an overlay such as a dialog or slide-in panel, change the "Shadow" property to "on".

Note: Not all components have the same auto layout settings.When placing a component into a slot you may need to resize the slot container from fixed to fill/hug for proper sizing and placement.

Child Container.name: Child Container
Child Container.description:
A container used for smaller groupings of content that sits on top of a parent container. This container must be manually resized.

NOTE: There is currently no coded version or documentation at this time.

Date Picker.name: Date Picker
Date Picker.description:
The date picker should be used as an option to adding inline dates via form fields. The calendar view date picker can help supplement date inputs. The date picker can be used when a start and stop date is being chosen or a series of days are being selected. 

The Date Picker days can be changed from default, today, and past/future days. The days can be manipulated using the right hand properties panel.

Dialog Screen Overlay.name: Dialog Screen Overlay
Dialog Screen Overlay.description: In order to clearly separate the dialog box from the standard screen content, we recommend that you overlay the screen with this component. This should make it clear that the user must dismiss the dialog before they can continue with other screen operations.

Dialog.name: Dialog
Dialog.description:
A Dialog Box interrupts app processing to prompt a user to confirm an action or acknowledge a piece of information. It displays information along with a set of buttons allowing users to Accept" or "Cancel the actions presented within the Dialog Box.

To add custom content, replace the Slot instances or the _dialog-default-footer with your own content. Scrollbars, a toolbar, and other features can be hidden and shown in the component layers.

Monitoring Icon.name: Monitoring Icon
Monitoring Icon.description: These icons represent objects, equipment, and concepts that are being administered or monitored. The purpose of these icons is to easily, concisely, and clearly visually communicate their status to users.

Pop Up Menu.name: Pop Up Menu
Pop Up Menu.description:
A Pop-Up Menu provides users with a quick way to access common actions for a highlighted item.

The arrow direction can be controlled in the Pop Up Container layer.

There are additional hidden menu options that can be turned on to create a bigger pop up menu.
States of menu options can be changed and menu dividers shown at the _menu-option layer level as well.

Pop Up Container.name: Pop Up Container
Pop Up Container.description:
A Pop Up provides users with a quick way to access additional information or actions regarding something on the UI on-click.

Pop Up Container contains a Slot so local component builds can be swapped into it.

Indeterminate Progress.name: Indeterminate Progress
Indeterminate Progress.description:
An indeterminate progress indicators is displayed as a continuously spinning circle with no strict percentage or timeframe labeled. This type of indicator is usually used when a process takes between 1 to 10 seconds unless the duration is known.

The progress text layer can be hidden and shown in the layers menu.

Determinate Progress.name: Determinate Progress
Determinate Progress.description:
A determinate progress indicator is displayed as a linear bar that dynamically fills in as the process gets closer to done. Specific percentages, amounts, or time can be indicated in surrounding text for more detailed progress reports. This type is recommended for processes longer than 10 seconds or when the duration of a process is known.

There are 3 variants provided for the 3 percentage increments. Inside the layers, the label text can be toggled off and on to show or hide on any variant.

Push Button.name: Push Button
Push Button.description:
Push buttons are a variant of the Switch that incorporate label and action into a single user interface element. Push buttons may provide a useful interface element where screen real-estate is at a premium.

We recommend that you use the default button heights.

Radio Button Group.name: Radio Button Group
Radio Button Group.description:
Grouped version of radio buttons that allows for a joint error state, as well as default and disabled with border and without.

The radio control check and labels can be shown and hidden from the layer menu. Group borders can be toggled off and on using the properties tab on the right hand panel.

Radio Button.name: Radio Button
Radio Button.description:
Use Radio Buttons for mutually exclusive choices. If the user can make more than one choice, use Checkboxes instead.

The radio control checks and labels can be shown and hidden from the layer menu.

Horizontal Scrollbar.name: Horizontal Scrollbar
Horizontal Scrollbar.description: Scrollbars are styled through the global astro CSS, but they are not a component of the Astro design system. There is no corresponding page at astrouxds.com.

Vertical Scrollbar.name: Vertical Scrollbar
Vertical Scrollbar.description: Scrollbars are styled through the global astro CSS, but they are not a component of the Astro design system. There is no corresponding page at astrouxds.com.

Segmented Button.name: Segmented Button
Segmented Button.description:
Segmented Buttons allow users to select one item at a time, from two to four options.

Segments can be hidden or shown at the _segment layer to change the number of segments in the component. Different states for the segments are also available in the _segment layer.

Multi-select Menu.name: Multi-select Menu
Multi-select Menu.description:
Multi-select menu allows users to search for specific items and the ability to select multiple items at once. 

Caret state and the select menu input state and sizes can be adjusted in the _select-input layer. Menus are turned on and off in the layer menu (_menu layer). Menu options can be adjusted at the _menu and _menu-option layers.

NOTE: There is currently no coded version or documentation at this time.

Select Menu.name: Select Menu
Select Menu.description:
Select Menus allow users to select a single value from a list.

Caret state and the select menu input state and sizes can be adjusted in the _select-input layer. Menus are turned on and off in the layer menu (_menu layer). Menu options can be adjusted at the _menu and _menu-option layers.

Dual Range Slider.name: Dual Range Slider
Dual Range Slider.description:
A Slider with two thumbs, allowing a selection to be made as a continuous or discrete range between the two end points.


To manipulate the range, select the ADJUSTMENT LAYER and adjust the space between value in the auto layout panel.


To turn on or off individual text or discrete markers, show/hide the layers in the layers panel.

Slider.name: Slider
Slider.description:
A Slider allows users to choose from a range of continuous or discrete values arranged from minimum to maximum.


To turn on or off individual text or discrete markers, show/hide the layers in the layers panel.

Switch.name: Switch
Switch.description: A Switch toggles between two mutually exclusive states such as "On" or "Off." Unlike a checkbox, a switch initiates an action with immediate effect without requiring a "Save" or "Submit" action.

Tab Small.name: Tab Small
Tab Small.description:
Tabs in Astro Applications are used to divide major areas of content and to indicate work process.

By default, the width of tabs adjust to their content. You can adjust the size to have fixed-width tabs. In order to re-apply auto-sized tabs, you need to select the component, go to the Constraints and resize section, and change the constraints to Hug contents.

Tab Large.name: Tab Large
Tab Large.description:
Tabs in Astro Applications are used to divide major areas of content and to indicate work process.

By default, the width of tabs adjust to their content. You can adjust the size to have fixed-width tabs. In order to re-apply auto-sized tabs, you need to select the component, go to the Constraints and resize section, and change the constraints to Hug contents.

Table.name: Table
Table.description:
A prebuilt table made out of Table Columns or Rows that can be detached into Table Cells and then edited in your own UI.

Note: Changing between the two variants (columns and rows) will reset the Table Cells involved.

For quick prototyping purposes, the header cells remain a fixed height unless text wraps in a cell. Since this component is made out of columns, other header cells will need to be changed manually to match the height of the wrapped text cell. To change this, detach the component and edit the Table Cells.

Table Row.name: Table Row
Table Row.description: A prebuilt table row that can be detached into Table Cells and then edited in your own UI.

Table Column.name: Table Column
Table Column.description: A prebuilt table column that can be detached into Table Cells and then edited in your own UI.

Table Cell.name: Table Cell
Table Cell.description:
Table Cells to create your own columns, rows, and tables. 

Borders and top shadow for first row cells can be hidden/shown from the layer list.

Table Cells should be a minimum of 32 px high for body cells and 40 px high for header cells.

Table Content.name: Table Content
Table Content.description:
Pre-made content options for Table Cells. 

To change the alignment of the pre-made cell content, change the auto-layout positioning in the Positioning Container layer.

To change the text alignment of pre-made cell content, change the alignment on the Text layer.

Tag 4.name: Tag 4
Tag 4.description:
Tags help users quickly identify important information related to an item and categorize items by keywords.

When using tags, colors should not overlap status or classification colors. For further color guidance, please refer to the usage documentation. 

Non-Status Tags are not a primary component in the Astro UX Design System. They are provided here as a convenience.

Tag 3.name: Tag 3
Tag 3.description:
Tags help users quickly identify important information related to an item and categorize items by keywords.

When using tags, colors should not overlap status or classification colors. For further color guidance, please refer to the usage documentation. 

Non-Status Tags are not a primary component in the Astro UX Design System. They are provided here as a convenience.

Tag 2.name: Tag 2
Tag 2.description:
Tags help users quickly identify important information related to an item and categorize items by keywords.

When using tags, colors should not overlap status or classification colors. For further color guidance, please refer to the usage documentation. 

Non-Status Tags are not a primary component in the Astro UX Design System. They are provided here as a convenience.

Tag 1.name: Tag 1
Tag 1.description:
Tags help users quickly identify important information related to an item and categorize items by keywords.

When using tags, colors should not overlap status or classification colors. For further color guidance, please refer to the usage documentation. 

Non-Status Tags are not a primary component in the Astro UX Design System. They are provided here as a convenience.

Tag 0.name: Tag 0
Tag 0.description:
Tags help users quickly identify important information related to an item and categorize items by keywords.

When using tags, colors should not overlap status or classification colors. For further color guidance, please refer to the usage documentation. 

Non-Status Tags are not a primary component in the Astro UX Design System. They are provided here as a convenience.

Status Tag.name: Status Tag
Status Tag.description:
Tags help users quickly identify important information related to an item and categorize items by keywords.

Status Tags such as Pass, Fail, and Unknown are commonly used to show the status of a system such as an antennae or another communication device. The other Status Tags line up with Astro's Status System.

Hero Number.name: Hero Number
Hero Number.description: A table can be configured with a tall header with large hero numbers (if the count of some type is important to know at a glance) or with a compact header if vertical space is at a premium.

Error Text.name: Error Text
Error Text.description: Error Text provides contextual or instructional information about an error for an invalid form element.

Help Text.name: Help Text
Help Text.description: Help Text provides contextual or instructional information for a form element.

Left Label.name: Left Label
Left Label.description:
Label for use to the left of a form element or grouping

To turn the required asterisk, the icon or (Optional) message on or off, go into the layers menu and use the show/hide feature.

Top Label.name: Top Label
Top Label.description:
Label for use to the top of a form element or grouping

To turn the required asterisk, the icon or (Optional) message on or off, go into the layers menu and use the show/hide feature.

Textarea.name: Textarea
Textarea.description: Multi-line text input that can be resized by the user. Follow text input best practices.

Toast stack.name: Toast stack
Toast stack.description: The Toast Stack is a group of toasts displayed in a vertical arrangement.

Toast.name: Toast
Toast.description: Toasts are time-based, non-modal notifications that display a short message to the user.

Tooltip.name: Tooltip
Tooltip.description: A Tooltip is a message box that provides a concise amount of relevant contextual information about an associated UI element. Tooltips are activated by hovering over, focusing on, or tapping an element.

Tree Group.name: Tree Group
Tree Group.description:
Trees present a hierarchical set of related items and allow users to explore and select items within that hierarchy.

By default, text in a Tree Item is set to truncate. The text can be set to wrap by selecting the text, opening the Figma Text Settings panel and setting Resizing to Auto Height.

Tree Item.name: Tree Item
Tree Item.description:
Trees present a hierarchical set of related items and allow users to explore and select items within that hierarchy.

By default, text in a Tree Item is set to truncate. The text can be set to wrap by selecting the text, opening the Figma Text Settings panel and setting Resizing to Auto Height.

To maintain the color union, Icons have to be swapped out under the color union layer. Use command+left click to go down to the bottom layer faster and select the icon directly under the color union layer, then swap to the icon of your choice.

Breadcrumbs.name: Breadcrumbs
Breadcrumbs.description:
Breadcrumbs are a secondary navigation pattern that provides users with an ordered list of links that helps visualize locational awareness within a sites hierarchy. Breadcrumbs provide a user with their current site location and allows them to quickly navigate to a parent page or previous step.

Each Breadcrumb Item is comprised of a clickable page link followed by a dividing icon. However, the final Breadcrumb Item, representing the current page, has a static text label and no divider.

Breadcrumb Item.name: Breadcrumb Item
Breadcrumb Item.description: Each Breadcrumb Item is comprised of a clickable page link followed by a dividing icon. However, the final Breadcrumb Item, representing the current page, has a static text label and no divider.

Stacked Bar Chart.name: Stacked Bar Chart
Stacked Bar Chart.description:
The standard way to show a statistical distribution - keep the gaps between columns small to highlight the shape of the data. 

For resizing the chart, it is recommended to use the scale tool      when resizing elements so that they remain proportional and circular.

If the text is not needed, then we recommend turning the text layer visibility off to hide the text. 

NOTE: This is a design-only component. Any coding of data visualizations is custom and not provided by the Astro team.

Grouped Vertical Bar Chart.name: Grouped Vertical Bar Chart
Grouped Vertical Bar Chart.description:
A Grouped Bar Chart allows for more  multiple data elements to be compared in a bar chart format.

For resizing the chart, it is recommended to use the scale tool      when resizing elements so that they remain proportional and circular.

If the text is not needed, then we recommend turning the text layer visibility off to hide the text. 

NOTE: This is a design-only component. Any coding of data visualizations is custom and not provided by the Astro team.

Vertical Bar Chart.name: Vertical Bar Chart
Vertical Bar Chart.description:
Vertical bar charts display the ranks of values more easily when sorted in order.

For resizing the chart, it is recommended to use the scale tool      when resizing elements so that they remain proportional and circular.

If the text is not needed, then we recommend turning the text layer visibility off to hide the text. 

NOTE: This is a design-only component. Any coding of data visualizations is custom and not provided by the Astro team.

Horizontal Bar Chart.name: Horizontal Bar Chart
Horizontal Bar Chart.description:
Horizontal bar charts display the ranks of values more easily when sorted in order.

For resizing the chart, it is recommended to use the scale tool      when resizing elements so that they remain proportional and circular.

If the text is not needed, then we recommend turning the text layer visibility off to hide the text. 

NOTE: This is a design-only component. Any coding of data visualizations is custom and not provided by the Astro team.

Line Chart.name: Line Chart
Line Chart.description:
For resizing the chart, it is recommended to use the scale tool      when resizing elements so that they remain proportional and circular.

If the text is not needed, then we recommend turning the text layer visibility off to hide the text. 

NOTE: This is a design-only component. Any coding of data visualizations is custom and not provided by the Astro team.

Scatter Plot Chart.name: Scatter Plot Chart
Scatter Plot Chart.description:
Scatter charts plot points on a graph. When the user hovers over the points, tooltips are displayed with more information.

For resizing the chart, it is recommended to use the scale tool      when resizing elements so that they remain proportional and circular.

If the text is not needed, then we recommend turning the text layer visibility off to hide the text. 

NOTE: This is a design-only component. Any coding of data visualizations is custom and not provided by the Astro team.

Scatter Plot Point.name: Scatter Plot Point
Scatter Plot Point.description:
Scatter plots are a point that can be used on a graph to show measurement on a vertical and horizontal plane. 

NOTE: This is a design only component. Any coding of data visualizations is custom and not provided by the Astro team.

Fill Gauge.name: Fill Gauge
Fill Gauge.description:
The Fill Gauge is a circular shape that represents a percentage value of a whole. May also be depicted as a dial.

For resizing the chart, it is recommended to use the scale tool      when resizing elements so that they remain proportional and circular.

If the text is not needed, then we recommend turning the text layer visibility off to hide the text. 

NOTE: This is a design-only component. Any coding of data visualizations is custom and not provided by the Astro team.

Pie Chart.name: Pie Chart
Pie Chart.description:
Conveys part-to-whole data. Pie charts are very common, but research has shown that it may be difficult to accurately compare the size of the segments without supporting data points.

For resizing the chart, it is recommended to use the scale tool      when resizing elements so that they remain proportional and circular.

If the text is not needed, then we recommend turning the text layer visibility off to hide the text. 

NOTE: This is a design-only component. Any coding of data visualizations is custom and not provided by the Astro team.

Donut Chart.name: Donut Chart
Donut Chart.description:
Conveys part-to-whole data. Similar to a pie chart  but the center can be useful for additional information about the data (e.g. total).

For resizing the chart, it is recommended to use the scale tool      when resizing elements so that they remain proportional and circular.

If the text is not needed, then we recommend turning the text layer visibility off to hide the text. 

NOTE: This is a design-only component. Any coding of data visualizations is custom and not provided by the Astro team.

Legend Interactive Row.name: Legend Interactive Row
Legend Interactive Row.description: The Interactive Legend is used to help identify data points within a graph or chart. The added functionality over a static legend is that the Interactive Legend's items can be shown or hidden using the items checkbox.

Legend Static Row.name: Legend Static Row
Legend Static Row.description: When the data appearing in a chart contains multiple data series, it becomes more readable if they are shown in a legend. This helps in identifying each data series/data point in the chart.

Legend Interactive Column.name: Legend Interactive Column
Legend Interactive Column.description: The Interactive Legend is used to help identify data points within a graph or chart. The added functionality over a static legend is that the Interactive Legend's items can be shown or hidden using the items checkbox.

Legend Static Column.name: Legend Static Column
Legend Static Column.description: When the data appearing in a chart contains multiple data series, it becomes more readable if they are shown in a legend. This helps in identifying each data series/data point in the chart.

Global Status Bar.name: Global Status Bar
Global Status Bar.description:
The Global Status Bar is a full width view across the top of an application  an area commonly reserved for global status, global command, and top-level navigation. The Global Status Bar often includes: Application Name, Monitoring Icons, Top Level Navigation, and an Emergency Button.

Note: The GSB should be 96 px tall and we discourage vertically resizing.

Log.name: Log
Log.description: A Log is a tabular representation of application events and may include username, priority, equipment type, signal type, etc. As part of the Notification System, Logs provide sorting and filtering function for examining events.

Log Search.name: Log Search
Log Search.description: Default table text style and padding

Notification Banner.name: Notification Banner
Notification Banner.description:
Events that deserve user attention, but dont require a response, may be displayed in a Notification Banner.

Banners push content down instead of overlaying content and should span the width of the container the message is relevant to. So we do not recommend using more than 2 lines of text.

The left slot, status symbol, link text, and right icon can be hidden or shown in the layer menu. Layers like the left slot and the right icon can be traded out at the instance level for custom instance content as needed.

Notification Message.name: Notification Message
Notification Message.description:
For use for onscreen error messages along with validation text in long forms.

Note: This component is not available in code or on the Astro UXDS website.

Pagination.name: Pagination
Pagination.description:
Use Pagination only when necessary. Instead, think about editing the content to fit onto one page. If there is only one page, no Pagination is needed.

All layers can be hidden and shown to adjust the control to your needs. Hidden ellipses are present in the component if needed to shorten the pagination list when there is a large number of pages. 

Different states for the links are available in the _pagination-text layer.

Access Denied.name: Access Denied
Access Denied.description: If there are server-side errors when the user submits the sign in form, use an inline notification to display field-specific errors or a validation summary for errors that are not field-specific or for errors that apply to multiple fields and could present a security concern when inline.

SSO Sign In.name: SSO Sign In
SSO Sign In.description:
Single Sign On (SSO) consists of a field to identify the user, typically a username or email, and a button that submits the content for SSO verification. SSO sign ins are usually used in context of an organization that uses one master login to authenticate other logins within that system after initial verification. 

In order to access states such as invalid/disabled, go one layer deeper into the input level and adjust from there. Error and Help text are able to be turned on and off in the layers.

Simple Sign In.name: Simple Sign In
Simple Sign In.description:
The sign in component consists of a field to identify the user, typically a username or email, and a masked field for a unique passcode, as well as a button that submits the content.

In order to access states such as invalid/disabled, go one layer deeper into the input level and adjust from there. Error and Help text are able to be turned on and off in the layers.

Timeline.name: Timeline
Timeline.description: Timeline displays a sequence of realtime events during a fixed time span. The Playhead indicates the current time of day. Time Regions represent events.

Focus State.name: Focus State
Focus State.description:
Focus state communicates when a user has engaged or highlighted an interactive component by using a keyboard or voice command. Focus states enable a better experience for users with visual or motor impairments who rely on keyboard and voice to navigate through an application.

The Figma Focus State component is comprised of three variants  rectangle, square, and circle. Within each of these variants is an auto-layout slot which can be accessed through the property layers panel.  Components, such as buttons, can be swapped into the auto layout slot and the Focus State ring should hug that component.

If there is an issue with the appearance of the Focus State once a component is swapped in, an instance of the Focus State component can be laid on top and resized to the correct appearance.

Slot.name: Slot
Slot.description: A generic placeholder that can be traded out for a custom component.

Auto Layout Slot.name: Auto Layout Slot
Auto Layout Slot.description: A generic placeholder that can be traded out for a custom component.
